## Set up Firebase Firestore in Next.js

### 1. Create a Firebase project
- Go to https://console.firebase.google.com → click "Add project".
- Enable Google Analytics if desired (optional).
- In Project Settings → Your apps → click the Web icon (`</>`) → register your app.
- Copy the `firebaseConfig` object shown in the setup wizard.
- In the Firebase console sidebar → Build → Firestore Database → "Create database".
- Choose a region closest to your users (e.g., `us-central`, `europe-west`). Region cannot be changed later.
- Start in **test mode** for development (open reads/writes); switch to production rules before launch.

### 2. Install the Firebase SDK
- Install the client SDK:
  ```
  npm install firebase
  ```
- For server-side access (API routes, Server Components), also install the Admin SDK:
  ```
  npm install firebase-admin
  ```
- Do NOT install `firebase@8` or earlier — use Firebase v9+ (modular SDK) for tree-shaking and better TypeScript support.

### 3. Configure environment variables
- Add to `.env.local` (NEVER commit this file):
  ```
  # Client-side Firebase config (safe to expose — security is enforced by Firestore rules)
  NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY=your-api-key
  NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-project.firebaseapp.com
  NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
  NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-project.appspot.com
  NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=your-sender-id
  NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID=your-app-id

  # Admin SDK (server-side only — NEVER expose to client)
  FIREBASE_ADMIN_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
  FIREBASE_ADMIN_CLIENT_EMAIL=your-service-account@your-project.iam.gserviceaccount.com
  FIREBASE_ADMIN_PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----\n...\n-----END PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
  ```
- For the Admin SDK credentials: Firebase console → Project Settings → Service accounts → Generate new private key.
- The `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix exposes variables to the client bundle — only use it for the client config, never for Admin credentials.

### 4. Create the client-side Firebase app (`lib/firebase/client.ts`)
  ```ts
  import { initializeApp, getApps, getApp } from 'firebase/app';
  import { getFirestore } from 'firebase/firestore';

  const firebaseConfig = {
    apiKey: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY,
    authDomain: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN,
    projectId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID,
    storageBucket: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET,
    messagingSenderId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID,
    appId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID,
  };

  // Prevent duplicate app initialization in Next.js hot reload
  const app = getApps().length === 0 ? initializeApp(firebaseConfig) : getApp();

  export const db = getFirestore(app);
  ```
- The `getApps().length === 0` guard prevents "Firebase App named '[DEFAULT]' already exists" errors during Next.js hot reloads.

### 5. Create the Admin SDK client (`lib/firebase/admin.ts`)
  ```ts
  import { initializeApp, getApps, cert, App } from 'firebase-admin/app';
  import { getFirestore as getAdminFirestore } from 'firebase-admin/firestore';

  let adminApp: App;

  if (getApps().length === 0) {
    adminApp = initializeApp({
      credential: cert({
        projectId: process.env.FIREBASE_ADMIN_PROJECT_ID,
        clientEmail: process.env.FIREBASE_ADMIN_CLIENT_EMAIL,
        privateKey: process.env.FIREBASE_ADMIN_PRIVATE_KEY?.replace(/\\n/g, '\n'),
      }),
    });
  } else {
    adminApp = getApps()[0];
  }

  export const adminDb = getAdminFirestore(adminApp);
  ```
- The `replace(/\\n/g, '\n')` call is required — environment variables store newlines as literal `\n` and the private key needs real newlines.
- Only import from this file in API routes and Server Components — never in client components.

### 6. Define TypeScript types (`lib/firebase/types.ts`)
  ```ts
  import type { Timestamp } from 'firebase/firestore';

  export interface Post {
    id: string;
    title: string;
    content: string;
    authorId: string;
    createdAt: Timestamp;
    updatedAt: Timestamp;
  }

  export type PostInput = Omit<Post, 'id' | 'createdAt' | 'updatedAt'>;
  ```
- Always define types for your documents to catch schema drift early.
- Use `Timestamp` from `firebase/firestore` (client) or `FirebaseFirestore.Timestamp` (admin) for date fields — do NOT store dates as strings.

### 7. CRUD helpers (`lib/firebase/posts.ts`)
  ```ts
  import {
    collection, doc, getDocs, getDoc,
    addDoc, updateDoc, deleteDoc,
    serverTimestamp, query, orderBy, limit,
  } from 'firebase/firestore';
  import { db } from './client';
  import type { Post, PostInput } from './types';

  const postsRef = collection(db, 'posts');

  export async function getPosts(count = 20): Promise<Post[]> {
    const q = query(postsRef, orderBy('createdAt', 'desc'), limit(count));
    const snapshot = await getDocs(q);
    return snapshot.docs.map(d => ({ id: d.id, ...d.data() } as Post));
  }

  export async function getPost(id: string): Promise<Post | null> {
    const snap = await getDoc(doc(db, 'posts', id));
    return snap.exists() ? ({ id: snap.id, ...snap.data() } as Post) : null;
  }

  export async function createPost(input: PostInput): Promise<string> {
    const ref = await addDoc(postsRef, {
      ...input,
      createdAt: serverTimestamp(),
      updatedAt: serverTimestamp(),
    });
    return ref.id;
  }

  export async function updatePost(id: string, data: Partial<PostInput>): Promise<void> {
    await updateDoc(doc(db, 'posts', id), { ...data, updatedAt: serverTimestamp() });
  }

  export async function deletePost(id: string): Promise<void> {
    await deleteDoc(doc(db, 'posts', id));
  }
  ```
- Always use `serverTimestamp()` for `createdAt`/`updatedAt` — it uses Firestore server time, not the client clock.
- Use `query()` with `orderBy()` for sorted reads — never sort in JavaScript on large collections.

### 8. Real-time listener in a React Client Component
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
  import { collection, onSnapshot, query, orderBy } from 'firebase/firestore';
  import { db } from '@/lib/firebase/client';
  import type { Post } from '@/lib/firebase/types';

  export function PostList() {
    const [posts, setPosts] = useState<Post[]>([]);

    useEffect(() => {
      const q = query(collection(db, 'posts'), orderBy('createdAt', 'desc'));
      const unsubscribe = onSnapshot(q, (snapshot) => {
        setPosts(snapshot.docs.map(d => ({ id: d.id, ...d.data() } as Post)));
      });
      return unsubscribe; // cleanup on unmount
    }, []);

    return (
      <ul>
        {posts.map(p => <li key={p.id}>{p.title}</li>)}
      </ul>
    );
  }
  ```
- Always return the `unsubscribe` function from `useEffect` — failing to do so causes memory leaks.
- Real-time listeners (`onSnapshot`) consume Firestore reads continuously. Use them only for data that must update in real time; use `getDocs` for one-time reads.

### 9. Server-side read in a Next.js API route
  ```ts
  import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
  import { adminDb } from '@/lib/firebase/admin';

  export async function GET() {
    const snapshot = await adminDb.collection('posts').orderBy('createdAt', 'desc').limit(20).get();
    const posts = snapshot.docs.map(d => ({ id: d.id, ...d.data() }));
    return NextResponse.json(posts);
  }
  ```
- Use `adminDb` (Admin SDK) in API routes and Server Components — it bypasses Security Rules and uses server credentials.
- Use the client `db` only in Client Components with real-time listeners or user-authenticated requests.

### 10. Set Firestore Security Rules
- In the Firebase console → Firestore Database → Rules tab, set rules before going to production:
  ```
  rules_version = '2';
  service cloud.firestore {
    match /databases/{database}/documents {
      // Allow read/write only to authenticated users
      match /posts/{postId} {
        allow read: if true; // public read
        allow write: if request.auth != null && request.auth.uid == resource.data.authorId;
      }
    }
  }
  ```
- Test rules in the Firebase console → Rules Playground before publishing.
- Never leave test mode rules (`allow read, write: if true;`) in production.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Firebase App named '[DEFAULT]' already exists`** → You initialized the app twice. Use the `getApps().length === 0` guard from step 4.
- **`Missing or insufficient permissions`** → Firestore Security Rules are blocking the operation. Check rules match your auth state.
- **`FIREBASE_ADMIN_PRIVATE_KEY` is invalid** → The newline characters are escaped. Add `.replace(/\\n/g, '\n')` when reading the env var (step 5).
- **`Cannot find module 'firebase-admin'`** → Admin SDK not installed. Run `npm install firebase-admin`.
- **Real-time listener not updating** → You returned from `useEffect` without calling `unsubscribe`. Always return the listener cleanup.
- **TypeScript: `Property 'X' does not exist on type 'DocumentData'`** → Cast document data to your type: `d.data() as Post`. Or use a typed converter.
- **`NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY is not defined`** → Env vars not loaded. Check `.env.local` exists and restart the dev server.
- **High Firestore read counts** → You have a real-time listener on a large collection. Use `limit()` and paginate with `startAfter()`.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT use the Admin SDK (`firebase-admin`) in client components or expose Admin credentials to the browser — it bypasses all Security Rules.
- Do NOT store Admin SDK credentials (private key, client email) in `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` variables — they will be exposed in the client bundle.
- Do NOT leave Firestore in test mode (`allow read, write: if true`) in production — anyone can read and delete your entire database.
- Do NOT run `getDocs` inside a real-time listener callback for each document — this causes read amplification. Fetch all needed data in a single query.
- Do NOT store dates as strings in Firestore — use `serverTimestamp()` and `Timestamp` types for proper sorting and querying.
- Do NOT use `collection().get()` without `limit()` on large collections — it fetches every document and runs up your Firestore bill.
- Do NOT import from `firebase-admin` in Client Components — it is a Node.js-only SDK and will crash the browser bundle.
- Do NOT initialize multiple Firebase apps — always use the `getApps().length === 0` singleton guard.
